Orion Deputy Program Manager Mark Kirasich, right, talks to guests following the lecture. http://t.co/pzJzUpsV
Todd May, SLS Program Manager, talks to guests following the lecture. http://t.co/V4B3VHJm
Dumbacher: We're using the ISS to learn how to do deep space missions.
Q: How will u get Orion in space 4 ETF-1? Kirasich: We're looking at various launch vehicles that can get 2 the LEO we need 4 test flight.
Q from campers: Can you go to the Space Station? Kirasich: Yes, we can go there but our primary mission is beyond low-Earth orbit beyond ISS
Q from campers: What type of space suits r u working on? Kirasich: we're working on space suits 2 go outside of Orion & land on planets.
Q from space campers: Why a capsule? Dan Dumbacher, deputy assoc. admin. for Human Exploration: Capsule is best shape 4 deep space missions
Kirasich: Where are we going? Lagrange points, asteroids, moon and Mars.
Kirasich: Orion's Exploration Test Flight 1 will take place in 2014.
Kirasich: Orion test articles have undergone flight testing with drop tests @ Langley and parachute testing in Arizona.
Kirasich: Orion is shrouded by the Launch Abort System to protect astronauts.
Kirasich: Orion will carry a crew of four. The heat shield can withstand temps up to 6000 degrees F, nearly half as hot as the sun's surface
Kirasich: We're building the first human spacecraft to go beyond low-Earth orbit.
May: The ultimate destination we dream about is Mars.
May: SLS will have the power of 160,000 Corvette engines.
May: SLS will carry 154,000 - 286,000 pounds of payload.
May: We have a lot of existing technologies that will be used on the Space Launch System.
